                <pb n="1"/>
            <p>&#41;ESTABLISHED 1850.&#41;<lb/>
                THE HEBREW LEADER&#44;<lb/>
                294 BROADWAY&#44;<lb/>
                &#40;P. O. Box 514&#41;<lb/></p>
            <p>New York&#44; July 24<hi rend="sup">th</hi> 1879<lb/></p>
            <p>Revd. S. Morais<lb/>
                Philadelphia<lb/>
                Dear Sir<lb/></p>
            <p>It is proposed by<lb/> some respectable Jewish Gentlemen.<lb/> (orthodox&#41; to form a United States<lb/> Jewish Alliance&#44; having for its object&#44;<lb/> the establishment of a Jewish Academy &#38;<lb/> College in this City.  The forming of a Shechitor&#91;&#63;&#93;<lb/> Board for licensing Shochets&#44; a national<lb/> Jewish Labor Department or Employment Office.<lb/>  The erection of model family houses for the<lb/> Jewish poor&#44; etc etc.  What do you<lb/> think of such a project&#63;<lb/></p>  
            <p>With kind regards Very Respectfully<lb/>
                Dear Doctor<lb/>
                &#91;&#63;&#93;<lb/></p>
                
                <pb n="2"/>
            <p>Phila July 31<hi rend="sup">st</hi> 1879<lb/></p>
            <p>Dear Sir<lb/></p>
            <p>After a few days reflection&#44; I give you my views on the subject<lb/> of your favor of the 24<hi rend="sup">th</hi> inst.  A Jewish Academy is not needed<lb/> yet&#44; but all good men who wish the permanence of Judaism&#44; should favor &#34;free<lb/> schools&#44;&#34; give them a fresher &#91;crossed&#45;out&#93; impulse and see that with the knowledge of reading and translating Hebrew&#44; that<lb/> of the spirit of Mosaism&#44; and prophetism is imparted.  Ministers should labor<lb/> in their respective spheres to promote the study of higher branches of sacred literature&#44; inviting all without Minhag<lb/> distinctions to <del>benefit</del> avail themselves of the instruction.  A shechetah&#91;&#63;&#93; Board ought to exist but<lb/> its formation should &#91;crossed&#45;out&#93; bear the stamp of congregational authority.<lb/>  A meeting of <del>such of</del> &#91;&#63;&#93; leading congregations which the Rabbis and preachers who possess the qualifications<lb/> to examine&#44; be <del>present</del> asked to attend and receive a sanction from the representatives of &#91;&#63;&#93; of Jews&#44; would lend more weight to the <del>authority &#91;&#63;&#93; by</del> regulations of the Board&#44; and<lb/> get us a restraint on the &#91;&#63;&#93;&#44; not always tractable.<lb/></p>
            <p>About the practicability of a labor office&#44; &#38; the creation of model family houses&#44; I find<lb/> myself utterly incompetent to pronounce an opinion.  It strikes me&#44; however&#44; that we fall<lb/> very short in performing our duty towards the poor of our faith.  With the &#91;&#63;&#93; our coreligionists are said<lb/> to possess&#44; we ought to be bred to elevate the condition of <del>the</del> indigent Israelites.  We Philadel&#45;<lb/>phians have somewhat improved in the method of dispensing charity&#44; still we are very very<lb/> far from reaching perfection.  In a city like yours a fund created for the purposes you name<lb/> if managed by clear&#45;headed&#44; trust&#45;worthy and tender&#45;hearted persons might accomplish<lb/> a wonful&#91;sic&#63;&#93; abundance of good.  Hoping that your resolves may &#91;&#63;&#93; to the lasting ad&#45;<lb/>vantage of the cause you have espoused&#44; I remain<lb/></p>
            <p>yours respectfully<lb/>
                S. Morais<lb/></p>
            
            <pb n="3"/>
            <p>&#41;ESTABLISHED 1850.&#41;<lb/>
                The Leading Jewish Paper in America.<lb/>
